    brief:"A cost-reimbursable contract can carry different fee arrangements. Match the incentive to the situation.",
    exhibitTitle:"proc://costplus-6",
    exhibit:"<span class='cy'>COST-REIMBURSABLE FEE TYPES</span>\n  <span class='hl'>F1</span>  Costs reimbursed plus a fixed fee that does not change with cost\n  <span class='hl'>F2</span>  Costs reimbursed plus a fee that rises if targets are beaten\n  <span class='hl'>F3</span>  Costs reimbursed plus a subjective performance award\n\n<span class='dim'>Types: CPFF | CPIF | CPAF</span>",
    fields:[
      { label:"F1 (fixed fee regardless of cost) is...", options:["CPFF (Cost Plus Fixed Fee)","CPIF (Incentive Fee)","CPAF (Award Fee)","Fixed-Price"], answer:0, explain:"Cost Plus Fixed Fee pays allowable costs plus a predetermined fixed fee that does not vary with actual cost." },
      { label:"F2 (fee scales with beating targets) is...", hint:"Objective incentive formula.", options:["CPFF","CPIF","CPAF","T&M"], answer:1, explain:"Cost Plus Incentive Fee adjusts the fee by a formula when the seller beats (or misses) cost/performance targets." },
      { label:"F3 (subjective award for performance) is...", options:["CPFF","CPIF","CPAF","Fixed-Price"], answer:2, explain:"Cost Plus Award Fee grants a fee based on the buyer's subjective evaluation of seller performance." },
      { label:"Why does the buyer bear more risk in cost-reimbursable deals?", hint:"Compare to fixed-price.", options:["The seller guarantees the price","The buyer pays actual costs even if they overrun","There is no fee","Scope is always fixed"], answer:1, explain:"Because the buyer reimburses actual allowable costs, cost overruns fall mostly on the buyer, unlike fixed-price." }
    ],
    summary:"CPFF pays a fixed fee, CPIF rewards beating targets by formula, CPAF grants a subjective award, and the buyer carries the overrun risk."
